-- 
Bond Risk Decreases in Japan, Credit-Default Swap Prices Show

-- B y   K a t r i n a   N i c h o l a s
-- 
2011-05-30T00:58:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/bond-risk-decreases-in-japan-credit-default-swap-prices-show.html
The cost of insuring corporate bonds
against non-payment fell in  Japan , according to traders of
credit-default swaps.  The Markit iTraxx Japan index dropped 0.5 basis point to
123 basis points as of 9:38 a.m. in Tokyo, according to
Citigroup Inc. prices.  The Markit iTraxx Australia index was little changed at 111
basis points as of 10:40 a.m. in Sydney, Westpac Banking Corp.
prices show. The Markit iTraxx Asia index of 50 investment-grade
borrowers outside Japan was also little changed at 111.5 basis
points as of 8:35 a.m. in Singapore, according to Royal Bank of
Scotland Group Plc.  Credit-default swaps protect bond investors against
default, and traders use them to speculate on credit quality. A
drop signals improving perceptions of creditworthiness.  The swap contracts pay the buyer face value in exchange for
the underlying securities if a borrower fails to meet its debt
agreements. A basis point is 0.01 percentage point.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Katrina Nicholas in  Singapore  at 
 knicholas2@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
